segments.text: We still played the Corps game, you know, but when you got out there, it was loosened up, and most of the upperclassmen that came out there were pretty good guys, and they were wanting to have fun.
And Bonfire was almost entirely done by the Corps, was it?
Just about.
There was Walton Hall and Hart Hall.
There were some of the civilians, but most of it was organized and run by the Corps.
Then a senior ring.
Why is an Aggie ring so special?
It's probably as hard to explain as the Aggie spirit, but I know in my case, everybody looked forward.
The interesting thing back then is you didn't wear a senior ring, and we called it a senior ring.
You didn't wear it unless you were a senior.
You might have had a lot of hours.
You could get it as a junior, but you did not wear your ring, and now you see...

lots of juniors that'll have rings that'll be wearing them but that was another one of those traditions in the corps you better be wearing boots if you're wearing a senior ring the way i remember it all right i'm confused you couldn't get the ring until you had so many hours 90 say 95 now but back then uh i don't remember his 95 or what it was of course we took a lot more hours back then
But you did not wear it in your uniform as a junior.
It was a senior privilege to wear the Aggie ring.
And I also remember, speaking of the Aggie ring, I have what's called the old Army ring, as we referred to it.
It's the gold, but it's got the dark black inside it.
And now most of the rings you see are the shiny rings.
Well, we only had one person.
I remember when I was in school, took ammonia and it seems like cleaned it out.
But now this ring is not the popular ring.
And yours cost how much?
I can't remember.
My boots or my ring, I bought used boots.
One was 30 and one was 60, but it was not.
And where did you get that money?

Two or three times I went over, and I can't remember if I did it for either one of those, but I went over and took a short-term loan out at the YMCA, and you had a period of time to pay them back, and they wanted you
to give a dollar maybe if you borrowed $30 or $50, whatever.
A lot of times if you're going to Houston for a court trip, you go over and get $25.
But they didn't pressure you to pay anything back other than what you borrowed, but it was kind of customary you try to come up with another dollar.
And in terms of your college expenses, did your family pay that or did you earn some of it?
My family helped.
I worked every summer except when I went to summer camp in the oil field, and so I paid a pretty good portion of mine.
I never had an automobile.
I could have, but I never did ask my father for one because there were other people that had them.
As you recall, about how much did a year at A&M cost you then?
You know, it's really, really terrible.
I don't remember.
That's where I'm going to say again, when you talk to Bo and I'll introduce you to him, he can tell you exactly.
Do you have any senior ring stories?
Lost it or somebody somewhere at some exotic place spotted you, spotted an Aggie ring?
Well, I think, of course, from spending 21 years in the military, you ran into a lot of other Aggies.
And I'm one of these guys that I always watch for the ring.
And whether we're in Houston or wherever, we'll continue to try to see one.
And I'll talk to a fence post, as my kids say.
But I think most of the stories that you could tell is once you spot one, you start talking.
I know an Aggie story.
I was stationed at West Point in 65 when I was going to get out.
The colonel talked me into extending six months that was our battalion commander, and I went up there.
He was a West Pointer, and I went up there, and I worked for a lieutenant colonel that was out of Fort Campbell, Kentucky for the summer named Glenn Mitchell, an Aggie.
And then after I had...

gotten about halfway through the career course, I'd pretty well decided I was going to get out of the Army the next year, and I went up to Washington, D.C. because we had the Friday off to go visit Branch, and walked into my assignment officer was Glenn Mitchell, Lieutenant Colonel now, and he was a major when I worked for him.
Well, he sent me to A&M to teach ROTC, so a small world there, you know, how your life turns around because of this one Aggie.
But just I think the important thing I could say about being an Aggie, especially in the military, when you went in,
there was a reputation that was there that Aggies do well.
And I think when you first start off, it's kind of like graduating, or it was then, graduating from West Point.

You started off a step ahead of the other lieutenants because, and of course you had had the experience, the summer camp experience and everything else, which was a little bit more enhanced at summer camp because of your previous corps life and everything.
any people treasure their senior ring as much or more than any other institution.
And the diploma, I think the diploma too and everything, you know.
Why is that ring compared to most
Hey, it's hard to say, and you've been over here, and you know when we give out rings, and we might give out 3,000 rings.
Let's say, let's drop the number to 2,300 like we gave her out the other day.
It is amazing.
You will be sitting there for three hours handing them out, and young ladies just go crazy.

young men until you say something well I think that might be a keeper what do you think something and then you'll get that gleam in their eye but to every student it is it is important and I think they've
feel they've earned it, but I think all of a sudden they think they're joining the brotherhood or the sisterhood or something.
And it's just the one respected thing that you can probably put right up there with religion.
It's hard to explain.
I, as an outsider, think one of the keys is that it has changed so little in design so that it is a unifier
through the years, and whether you're a civilian or a corps or whether you major in this, that, or the other, it pulls everybody together.
You can start right there with the picture of the guy right there.
They met in his room when he was a cadet and came up with the design for the ring.
And that was before the turn of the century.
And the ring has changed very little.
You do see where the Eagles faced a different direction about three different times.
But the class of 30, of course, had the stone in it.
And if you go to the core center, you'll find a 29.
The quick war story I'll tell you, I never got to kush or desert for a couple of weeks because I didn't know which class had the stone, and somebody told me to go see Mr.
Gay.
I went to see him, and he picks up the phone and calls Rutter, who's the vice president that year, and all I could think was those sophomores are going to kill me.
And he said, he didn't know, but he said, call Lou.
And then Mr.
Gay called Lou, and Lou told him his class of 30.
Well, later when I was running the course center, I had one of the stone, ruby red type stones come in in a ring that said 29.
And I couldn't understand that because I had talked to Mr. Halbooty, who was the editor of the Longhorn, the yearbook in 30.
And

he had said that was the first year and then we found out it was from Harvey Striegler over here in admissions and his father had been a transfer student laid out a semester and he ordered his ring in 1930 but he was originally class 29 so but that with that one exception that year the ring has been basically the same uh senior boots you bought used
And you paid, you think, $30?
$30 seemed like what I paid, and the advantage of that, my roommate had new boots, and he had to shine the heck out of them.
Mine had probably been around 20 years, and all you had to do was put a little polish on them, and it'd really shine.
And did you pass them on?
I passed them on to someone for the same price.
I remember just like Midnight's, the juniors that we wore, I remember selling mine to Gary Halter when he was a class behind me.
And they were?

were all the boots the same color then no but uh we didn't have the uh really really uh dark boots that you the riding boots that you see everywhere else they were most all of them were a mahogany or a red or some but there were different different versions and you wore them officially the first time i probably the first time we wore them well we didn't wear them we didn't wear them except football games parades
You just didn't wear them to class.
You know, that was, that was considered.
Final review.
Oh, that was, you were king of the mountain, you know, and not only that about the boots, but, but there were so many privileges that went with that.
You could walk on grass anywhere.
You could walk anywhere you wanted, which may sound kind of corny, but it was a,
Did anybody special for you come that junior year when you went through final review?
No one.
My family came down when I graduated final review my senior year, but not my junior.
How did you feel then, that year?
Oh, I think I felt, you know, good from the standpoint that, of course, they came down my senior year, but I still had a year to graduate.
They came back again when I graduated and was commissioned.
Was the weather good for final year?
It was good, except my freshman year, and I don't know if there's ever been a time in the last...
60 years that final review was canceled, but it was canceled in 1959.
And if you look at the 1959 Aggieland, you'll see the drill field underwater.
We became sophomores up against the wall, standing at attention.
And I'll never forget the sophomores said, they referred to us now as pissheads.
They said, pissheads, hit your hole.
In other words, get out of the hall.
We're going to play hall hockey.
That's a junior privilege.
And we still laugh about it because all we could do is now we could leave the light on.
We could walk outside.
So if they were playing hall hockey, you walk outside and walk back in.
And you could wear your hat in the house, so you could put the hat on, look in the mirror, and you put on a different black belt.
But the other thing we did my freshman year that was very, very important, after final review, all the freshmen had to carry matches.
And you had to have one more than your age, I think it was, or something.
And we all went down to the corner of Dorm 2.
And we had a gathering, and we had a little bonfire.
We burned all the matches.
And final review was not postponed, but was literally canceled.
And it took them a good while to cancel it because it just kept raining and raining and raining.
And we were in dorm two waiting.
Nowadays, I think they'd have it in pouring down rain.
Commencement.
Why are A&M commencement special?
Oh, they're definitely special or you wouldn't see like the one the other day.
It's like trying to explain a lot of the other things.
It's a payback.
I think it's a payback to the parents because the smiles and they're always seem to be so happy to be back here.
And the students are proud of this place and it's just obvious.
But I think when we had meetings a few years ago and we were talking about senior finals, should seniors take finals, the other side of the coin was that should they have diplomas in the tube.
Because a lot of people felt it would be a lot easier to just mail them to them.
And I'll never forget one of the students telling a professor when he said, well, at other schools, they just mail them and they don't have all this work.
And the young girl said, sir, we're not another school.
And so it's the same way with graduation now.
I know with my son just graduating nearly two weeks ago, to see the majority of the students there for graduation and to see their parents there, it's unbelievable.
And some of them spent a lot of money coming, and everybody is important.
When you graduated, how many were there to see you graduate?
From my family, only my father and my stepmother.
Who else was there?

I think that most of the people, most of the people in my outfit had had family members come and had aunts and uncles, especially if you were from Fort Worth, Dallas, Austin, where it was driving distance.
Motels just didn't exist.
It was really tough.
You, it kind of goes back to a lot of the other things we were talking about.
You knew a professor
that you got to know, and I know that my family, the last stop we made leaving town was out at Mr. Penberthy's house because he was like a godfather to me, you know, here.
And your name was called, your hand was shaken, and you received your diploma.
In other words, it wasn't a piece of paper.
With my name on it, mm-hmm, and the degree.
Did anybody attempt any kind of pranks or hijinks at commencement?
No, I don't remember anything.
We had commissioning also, and I don't remember anything.
I don't remember the people writing things on top of their hats.
There might have been.
I just remember, of course, I remember final review.
which was very interesting because we always had the whooping and the yelling when they'd say pass and review.
Otherwise, it was pretty military up until that time.
And of course, it seemed like we always had a lot of people passing out because it was so hot and a lot of them had been out drinking.
And I'd be surprised if you remember the name of the commencement speaker.
Most people don't.
Commencement, I don't, but I think General Cassidy was the commissioning speaker.
commencement speaker, I don't remember.
And I should because I've heard that mentioned so many times.
At that point, how well did you feel A&M had prepared you for your future?
Oh, I felt very secure about going into the military because we'd been to summer camp and we had done so well
And I think we'd gotten a lot of additional training here, and you knew at that time the military situation in the world was changing, and I may have been different.
But it's kind of like I said, I'd worked five summers in the oil field, and I was kind of looking forward to the thought of seeing something outside of Jack County, because I had
I was 30 years old before I ever saw the Alamo, so that's hard to believe you could have come to school here at A&M.
Were you the first in your family, first generation in your family to graduate from college?
I was the first to graduate, yes.
And at the time you got your A&M degree, what did you think you were going to do professionally?
Well, I thought that I would go into the service and I was going to go back and work with my daddy who ran cattle and we had a lot of goats and I just planned on going back to Jacksonville.
I had no intentions of staying in.
No, and if I hadn't have been stationed at West Point, I went up there and
It extended six months, and then I volunteered to go to Vietnam.
And so then the next thing I knew, I spent 31 of the next 40 months in Nam, and came back here, taught ROTC, and met my wife in graduate school.
And then all of a sudden, the military, here I'd been in 10 years, and the military all of a sudden was probably the best decision I could make.
Of course, stay in, because.
All right, look back now over your life.

and interpret it in terms of what you now realize that a m did to prepare you for that life how well did a m prepare you and in what ways did they prepare you well well i would like to go back as when we had our discussion before i wish i had applied myself better academically when i was small my uh
Mother died when I was young.
I was really raised by my grandmother and so I didn't have any foundation for academics in high school at all or you couldn't go back to junior high.
So I wish I had really known how to study or had been forced to

apply myself better not procrastinate and things like that so I think that that probably I'd like to start there and but on the other hand is as your friend McCandless tells me he thinks I turned out all right considering but the bottom line is I think that it prepared me more than any just to deal with people

communicate with people to and to be conscientious now you may not you may not be the most eloquent person you may not be able to to do a lot of things other people can do but i think a m taught you that number one you got a job to do get the job done but don't step on other people's toes and if you have a problem there's somebody that you can ask for help you know and i think i think when you go back and you start looking at the five years you were here in school
There were a lot of problems, but there were always solutions, and there was always somebody.
It might have been your buddy, and it might have been this bonding together on different projects or different pranks or whatever.
So you're saying, you're implying that it taught you to be a team player?
Team player.

And have faith in yourself, too, because you can very easily feel that you're not capable of doing a lot of things, but when you go through four years of the Corps, where each year you're forced to take on new responsibilities or, on the same line, privileges that come with it.
Did it teach you how to judge people?
I think it probably taught you maybe not to judge people as to judge people, you know, unless you're really sure about the people.
Don't take a quick decision over something.
Judge is not the right word.
I used the wrong word.
But you, we came here, we came to Texas A&M, and the one thing you learned that most of the people that you dealt with

you could trust them or you knew you couldn't trust them right off the bat but you learn to give the benefit of the doubt to people and but you also learned in a hurry if somebody is the is a all these quickie salesman's is trying to get over on you or something like any can you depend on somebody
And it was pretty obvious in my career when I first went in the military, and you normally would have four or five lieutenants.
Well, it was pretty obvious if these people could be depended on.
Because lots of times if they're going to cover for you or they're going to help you on a project, you've got to have their participation.
When I used the word judge, what I was really trying to phrase was,
When you're trying to evaluate, to judge, to figure out who you can work with and who you can't,
I'm assuming that A&M taught you that their last name, where they worship, their family's income are not important.
That's what I was driving at.
Oh, yeah.
No question, but I think back of guys like the average cadet here is going to room
probably with three people, maybe four people, in a period of four years here.
Whereas if you're a civilian student, chances are you're going to do the very same thing because you're going to be living in the dorm, and then you're going to live off campus.
So you deal with a lot of people.
The advantage of the Corps is you just become very, very close with a large number of people.
In other words, you have a lot of roommates that may not be sharing the same room with you,
But you're sharing a lot of hours each day together.
So you do get to pretty well look at somebody and say, well, he's a good guy.
He may be rich, may be poor.
If you were a consultant to A&M's leadership now,
What advice would you give them about A&M, what they should do regarding it to make A&M's future strong, bright, positive?
Well, I would say the very first thing I would do, I would have a pretty good group of consultants

volunteer type people that love A&M that can give you advice and be very very careful don't don't just listen to the one that yells the loudest on the other hand I think you've got to sit down and you've got to realize that just how important and you've talked about this over and over some of the older ags what they felt it was like when they were here but but you do have to have this income
If we're going to do 2020 for an example, which we hope we were able to accomplish everything, but even some of the majority items there, it's going to take money.
And you don't want to offend someone over some small tradition or some small area that just because somebody would have come and said, oh, that's not important.
Well, it might be very, very important to someone.
But I think the...

The only advice I'd really say is get a lot of advice and then weigh it, but find somebody that you can at least trust that you can talk with and get their judgment because those people are around, and a lot of them are retired.
If you had the financial capability to make a major gift to A&M, for what purpose would you want your gift used?
Well, I think if I was giving a major gift to A&M, I would want it to go to students that wouldn't exactly be in the needy category, but students that are really having to work to come to school.
If you could say, you know, there's some kids pulling down two jobs.
If there was a way you could really know that
not based on how much income this family makes because the family may have a lot of children.

I would want it based on sophomores that have done fairly well academically but have a definite need, financial need, and I wouldn't go back and look at what their families make or anything like that.
Would their major matter?
Their major wouldn't matter.
The hardest thing would be how do you identify these students?
How do you identify that a student really needs something?

we usually say well are they driving a new car well yeah a lot of kids are driving new cars that's why a lot of kids are having to work make these car payments but but i think i think really we've got the extremes we've got the kids that make the excellent grades get scholarships the kids that are needy get scholarships and i see so many kids that that are in the middle that are having to having to work their tails off and they're not able to study although
I will say that my son this last semester carried 18 hours and five of them were in engineering, the other in economics, and he did very well because he stayed busy.
But it does hinder a lot of kids.
Getting near the end of that, to what former students, faculty, advisors, to what individuals
as you look back on your student days, do you feel most grateful and why?
Oh, I think I've talked about the three people that I was fortunate enough to work for in intramurals.
I think the

the professors that I had, and most of them were in the College of Agriculture, even though they carried on over into educational psychology, but those people taught the classes, not, not, I didn't have a student,

or other assistant teaching that class such as a ta the i had the i had the the professor and i think and i think most cases we had the professors in in in my days in nearly all the classes but uh were there did you have any as a student did you have any experience that you now know that that experience was a real fork in the road
Well, I think Dr. Potts put me on probation to go to class.
You know, I think I had been here two years, and I was surprised anybody even knew I was in school, you know, really.
So that was very... Oh, very, very beneficial.
And I have done that to many, many cadets that I've caught.
I've put them, which I legally couldn't probably do over in the Commandant's office,
But I put a number of students on no cut.
And I've taught the class how to succeed in college.
And I would always say, you get one absence in my class, period, period.
And I got away with it.
But they came to class because they understood.
Goodness knows what we've overlooked.
I hope we haven't overlooked much.
Well, my last question is, what feelings do you carry in your heart today for Texas A&M?
Well, I think I carry like most of them do.
I think one of the problems that I have is I live here.

I hear everything and I sometimes think it'd be so nice to be away from here with just good memories and not not having to pick up the paper in here and listen to whether whether it could be a former student that's upset and if they are all upset they got email now and you have to listen to everything so I still think I uh
I have the same love for A&M I've always had.
I have a love for the Corps.
I just think that I'm here where I hear too many negatives now and hear people complaining and griping about everything.
And nearly everything, for an example, the Faculty Senate does is, I think, is outstanding because that's why we're here.
We're here for academics.
But every once in a while, you might have a meeting of the whole, or somebody brings out something.
Then your blood starts boiling again.
And then you think.
But that can be over these 700 student organizations, which some of them you say, why in the world do we have that organization?
But you feel very optimistic about the future?
I feel very optimistic.
And as I say, I think that as long as we continue moving with the students,
being involved like they are, we're in good shape.
And proud and grateful.
Proud and grateful.
And as long as the girls stay in the leadership roles like we've been seeing lately, it's going to work well.
I throw that out not only as a joke, but there's a lot of truth to it, too.
Let's quit there.
